<section class="card">
  <h2>About Sweet Corn</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Heat-hungry warm-season crop—maturity depends on seasonal heat accumulation.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Sweet corn is frost-tender and killed at 32°F (0°C).</strong>
    In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), viability depends on two factors: total frost-free season length and accumulated Growing Degree Days (GDD). Corn matures on a heat schedule more than a calendar schedule.
  </p>

  <p>
    In cooler or shorter summers, even labeled “70-day” corn can drift later if heat accumulation is weak. That’s why short-season success is primarily about variety selection and heat budget, not just planting early.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 2–4 weeks after last frost (soil consistently warm)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 70–100 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> None (killed at 32°F / 0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline planning ranges. Soil temperature and summer heat strength strongly influence actual maturity timing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature & Soil Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minimum soil temperature:</strong> ~60°F (16°C) for reliable germination</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 70–90°F (21–32°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below 60°F (16°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Freeze damage:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Corn dislikes cold soil and stalls in cool nights. Early planting into marginal soil often delays emergence and shrinks your risk margin later in the season.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~1,200–1,800+ GDD (base 50), depending on hybrid length</p>

  <p>
    Sweet corn is one of the clearest examples of heat-dependent maturity. Hybrids are often labeled by days,
    but GDD more accurately reflects whether your climate can finish the crop before first frost.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the combined frost + heat framework, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Depending on hybrid, sweet corn typically requires <strong>70–100 frost-free days</strong>.
    However, without sufficient GDD accumulation, labeled days-to-maturity can drift later.
  </p>

  <p>
    In marginal climates, even if the frost-free window appears long enough, weak seasonal heat can prevent full kernel development before first frost.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Only with early hybrids and strong summer heat</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Often, unless GDD accumulation is high</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Rarely effective; heat accumulation is the limiting factor</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Corn has no frost tolerance buffer. A freeze at 32°F (0°C) can end the crop immediately and prevent kernels from finishing.
    First frost is a hard seasonal boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Select early-maturity hybrids (70–80 day types)</li>
    <li>Wait for warm soil before planting to avoid emergence delays</li>
    <li>Plant in full sun to maximize effective heat accumulation</li>
    <li>Avoid shaded or wind-exposed microclimates that reduce heat gain</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, sweet corn is viable when your frost-free window provides enough time and your seasonal heat budget provides sufficient GDD to reach maturity before 32°F (0°C).
    If either time or heat budget is marginal, risk increases significantly.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can corn survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Corn is frost-sensitive and can be damaged or killed at 32°F (0°C).
  </p>

  <h3>Why didn’t my corn mature before frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Most commonly, either the hybrid required more GDD than your climate provided, or early-season cold delayed development and reduced buffer.
  </p>

  <h3>Are “70-day” corn varieties safe in short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Sometimes—but only if your seasonal GDD accumulation matches the hybrid’s heat requirement. Days-to-maturity alone can be misleading in cool summers.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Sweet corn is strongly heat-dependent—GDD matters more than calendar days.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: ~1,200–1,800+ GDD (base 50), 70–100 frost-free days.</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + hybrid requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>